This document describes how to make live changes to the running config and save them to persist without the need to remove the SD card and flip the write-protect switch. This guide assumes you have already followed the steps to get config persistance working with a write-protected SD card found in the Current-Status document.

This guide utilizes an EEM script baked into the SD Card read only config that copies a config file from flash and merges it with the running config upon startup.

1. Make sure you SD card has write access enabled.
2. Copy your running config to a new file in flash: eg. flash:current-conf
3. Create an EEM script that runs on startup and copies this file to the running config. eg.
  event manager applet BOOT_COPY_CONF authorization bypass
    description "Copies current-conf to running-config on startup"
    event timer cron cron-entry "@reboot"
    action 1.0 cli command "enable"
    action 2.0 cli command "configure terminal"
    action 3.0 cli command "file prompt quiet"
    action 4.0 cli command "end"
    action 5.0 cli command "copy flash:current-conf running-config"
    action 6.0 cli command "configure terminal"
    action 7.0 cli command "no file prompt quiet"
    action 8.0 cli command "end"
    action 9.0 syslog msg "EEM: Successfully merged flash:current-conf into running-config"
4. (optional) Create aliases to make saving the config easier 
  alias exec wr copy running-config flash:current-conf
  alias exec write memory copy running-config flash:current-conf
5. Write this config to your startup config on you SD card.
6. Remove SD card and adapter and set back to write-protected.
7. reload

    
